   We use a “normalized” DP convention throughout: each child call returns a DP vector where  
      dp[k] = real_max_sum_for_k_picks − P[k].  
   When both children exist we correctly do a convolution and then call `normalize(dp)` exactly once, to maintain that invariant.  
   However, in the branches where only one child exists (i.e., the other subtree is empty), the code mistakenly invokes `normalize(...)` **again** on a vector that has already been normalized by the child. This double subtraction of `P[k]` corrupts the DP values (it effectively subtracts the prefix sums twice), producing wildly incorrect answers (e.g. −7 instead of 9 in the sample).

